04674nam a22005415i 9780773584037DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735840377 a10.1515/97807735840372doi  a(DE-B1597)657182  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHC118.M6bS94 2015eb 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a330.9714/282231 aSweeny, Robert C.H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy Did We Choose to Industrialize? :bMontreal, 1819-1849 /cRobert C.H. Sweeny. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b72 figures, 3 fold-out maps, 10 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Quebec/Études d'histoire du Québec ;v2900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPoints of Departure -- tColonial States -- tInternal Dynamics -- tCuvier’ Feather -- tAgency and Constraint -- t“C’est un travil dont je n’avais pas d’idée!” -- tTowards a Cubist Portrait -- tImaginary Lines -- tAn Industrial City -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe choice to industrialize has changed the world more than any other decision in human history. And yet the three prevailing explanations - the technical (new energy sources), the Marxist (new social relations), and the neo-liberal (people became more industrious) - are inadequate in making sense of this fundamental change. In mid-nineteenth-century Montreal, as in other early industrializing societies, change occurred as a result of the choices people made when faced with unprecedented opportunities and constraints. Montreal was the first colonial city to industrialize. Its overlapping French and English legal traditions mean that people's actions were exceptionally well documented for a North American city. Robert Sweeny’s novel reading of sources like city directories, ordinance surveys, monetary protests, and apprenticeship contracts leads him to develop important critiques of both mainstream and progressive historiography. He shows how the choice to industrialize was tied to the development of completely new ways of thinking about the world on three inter-related levels: how should we relate to each other, to property, and to nature? In Montreal, as in all the other early industrializing societies, thought preceded action. Sweeny illuminates the personal and familial decisions that tens of thousands of people made by the mid-nineteenth century which already prefigured much of what industrialized Montreal would look like in 1880. At a moment when global conflict is tied to resources and climate change, Sweeny shows how fundamental decision making can determine widespread social change. Informed by four decades of scholarship, Why Did We Choose to Industrialize? Is a politically engaged argument about history, a sustained reflection on sources and method in historical practice, and a singular vantage point on the ideas that have shaped historical understandings of industrialization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndustrial revolutionzQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aIndustrial revolutionzQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aIndustrial revolution. 0aIndustrializationxSocial aspectszQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aIndustrializationxSocial aspectszQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aIndustrializationzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistory. 0aIndustrializationzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358403740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/